        <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="4">
            <title>service procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid property damage, personal injury or death, park the vehicle on a flat level surface,
                        set the parking brake, chock the wheels and turn the engine off.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>Batteries expel explosive gases. Keep sparks, flames, burning cigarettes, or other ignition
                        sources away at all times. Always wear safety glasses and a face shield when working near
                        batteries to avoid property damage, personal injury or death.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect the negative cable from the battery.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Locate and remove the flywheel housing access plate, and with a 5/8 inch Allen wrench
                    remove the threaded plug from the engine flywheel housing. The access plate and plug are on the
                    passenger side of the flywheel housing (Figure 1 and Figure 2).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f049101" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/G049101.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                         scalefitheight="328px"/>
                <caption>Figure 1. Bottom View of Flywheel Housing on Passenger Side, 5/8 Inch Allen Wrench Used to
                    Remove Flywheel Housing Plug
                </caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f049102" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/G049102a.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="328px"/>
                <caption>Figure 2. Plug and Access Cover Removed from Flywheel Housing</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Plug Removed</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Access Cover Removed</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Caterpillar has a special tool, Part Number 9S9082, which will expedite rotating the flywheel
                        in the next step.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">With Caterpillar special tool, Part Number 9S9082, or a suitable pry bar engage the
                    flywheel ring gear (Figure 3) and rotate the flywheel until a flex plate mounting bolt is centered
                    in the plug hole.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f049103" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/G049103.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                         scalefitheight="328px"/>
                <caption>Figure 3. Rotating the Flywheel with Pry Bar</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>Use extreme care when removing or installing the flex plate mounting bolts. If the bolt is
                        dropped inside the housing and cannot be retrieved, the transmission must be removed to retrieve
                        the bolt.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the flex plate mounting bolt with a 13 mm socket (Figure 4).</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f049104" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/G049104.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                         scalefitheight="328px"/>
                <caption>Figure 4. Remove Flex Plate Mounting Bolt</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect the removed bolt for wear and with the aid of a mirror look through the plug
                    hole to determine if the condition of the flex plate mounting hole is elongated from wear:
                </para>
                <para>
                    <emph type="bold">NOTE: Wear is defined as excessive wear or gouging under the head of the bolt
                        where the threaded length starts and elongation of the mounting holes in the flex plate.
                    </emph>
                </para>
                <seqlist>
                    <item>
                        <para>If the bolt and flex plate
                            <emph type="bold">do not</emph>
                            show wear from lack of clamp load, install new bolts from the kit. Tighten to 19 to 24
                            Lbf-ft (26 to 32 Nm). Go to Step 6.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <para>If the bolt and/or flex plate show excessive wear from lack of clamp load, go to Step 8.
                        </para>
                    </item>
                </seqlist>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Repeat Steps 2 - 5A to replace the remaining bolts.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">When the 12 mounting bolts are replaced, reinstall the flywheel plug, tighten to 14 to
                    17 Lbf-ft (19 to 23 Nm), and reinstall the flywheel access cover. Go to Step 9.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Due to the wear of the flex plate mounting bolts and/or flex plate it is necessary to
                    replace the flex plate and mounting bolts. This will require removing the transmission to install a
                    new flex plate and 12 new mounting bolts. Tighten the mounting bolts to 19 to 24 Lbf-ft (26 to 32
                    Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reconnect the negative cable to the battery.</para>
            </step1>
        </svcproc>
